04802nam a22006495i 9780292762893DE-B159720211027022714.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211027t20211991txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802927628937 a10.7560/7512172doi  a(DE-B1597)587613  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 4aNA1996b.W48 1990 7aARC0050802bisacsh04a720/.9732201 aWilliamson, Roxanne Kuter, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aAmerican Architects and the Mechanics of Fame /cRoxanne Kuter Williamson. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©1991  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPlates -- tCharts -- tTables -- tAcknowledgments -- tONE A Network of Connections -- tTWO The Time as Well as the Place -- tTHREE A Consensus of Who Is Famous and Who Is Not: The Index of Fame -- tPART I Case Studies: The Apprenticeship Connection -- tFOUR Louis Sullivan -- tFIVE Frank Lloyd Wright -- tSIX Henry Hobson Richardson -- tSEVEN McKim, Mead & White -- tEIGHT Latrobe and His Descendants -- tNINE The Bulfinch and Renwick Lines -- tTEN The European Immigrant Masters in the Twentieth Century -- tELEVEN Louis Kahn -- tTWELVE The Loners -- tPART II Conventional Wisdom about Architects9 Predispositions for Fame -- tTHIRTEEN Connections: Family, Friends, Schools -- tFOURTEEN Self-promotion and Publicity -- tFIFTEEN Other, Weaker Patterns -- tSIXTEEN The Historians as Fame Makers -- tSEVENTEEN Afterword on the Fame-Making System -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex of Architects0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhy does one talented individual win lasting recognition in a particular field, while another equally talented person does not? While there are many possible reasons, one obvious answer is that something more than talent is requisite to produce fame. The "something more" in the field of architecture, asserts Roxanne Williamson, is the association with a "famous" architect at the moment he or she first receives major publicity or designs the building for which he or she will eventually be celebrated. In this study of more than six hundred American architects who have achieved a place in architectural histories, Williamson finds that only a small minority do not fit the "right person–right time" pattern. She traces the apprenticeship connection in case studies of Louis Sullivan, Frank Lloyd Wright, Henry Hobson Richardson, the firm of McKim, Mead & White, Latrobe and his descendants, the Bulfinch and Renwick Lines, the European immigrant masters, and Louis Kahn. Although she acknowledges and discusses the importance of family connections, the right schools, self-promotion, scholarships, design competition awards, and promotion by important journals, Williamson maintains that the apprenticeship connection is the single most important predictor of architectural fame. She offers the intriguing hypothesis that what is transferred in the relationship is not a particular style or approach but rather the courage and self-confidence to be true to one's own vision. Perhaps, she says, this is the case in all the arts. American Architects and the Mechanics of Fame is sure to provoke thought and comment in architecture and other creative fields.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Okt 2021) 0aArchitects and patronszUnited States. 0aArchitectsxSelection and appointmentzUnited States. 0aArchitectural services marketingzUnited States. 7aARCHITECTURE / History / Contemporary (1945-).2bisacsh40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292762893423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292762893/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHAL